2 Process

Read the HTSeq files in a matrix

res <- mclapply(dir("htseq",pattern="*STAR.txt",full.names=TRUE),function(fil){
  read.delim(fil,header=FALSE,stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
},mc.cores=max(mcaffinity()))
names(res) <- gsub("_STAR\\.txt|.*XX_","",dir("htseq",pattern="*STAR.txt"))

Sort the samples

samples <- samples[match(names(res),samples$Filename),]

Get the count table

addInfo <- c("__no_feature","__ambiguous","__too_low_aQual","__not_aligned","__alignment_not_unique")
sel <- match(addInfo,res[[1]][,1])
count.table <- do.call(cbind,lapply(res,"[",3))[-sel,]
colnames(count.table) <- names(res)
rownames(count.table) <- res[[1]][,1][-sel]

Extract the HTSeq stat lines

count.stats <- do.call(cbind,lapply(res,"[",2))[sel,]
colnames(count.stats) <- names(res)
rownames(count.stats) <- addInfo
count.stats <- rbind(count.stats,aligned=colSums(count.table))
count.stats <- count.stats[rowSums(count.stats) > 0,]

Plot the stats

pal=brewer.pal(6,"Dark2")[1:nrow(count.stats)]
par(mar=c(7.1,5.1,4.1,2.1))
barplot(as.matrix(count.stats),col=pal,beside=TRUE,las=2,main="read proportion",
        ylim=range(count.stats) + c(0,2e+7))
legend("top",fill=pal,legend=rownames(count.stats),bty="n",cex=0.8)

par(mar=mar)

boxplot(unlist(count.stats["aligned",]/colSums(count.stats)),main="aligned reads",ylab="percent aligned",ylim=c(0,1))

25.7% of the genes are not expressed out of a total of 70736 genes

sel <- rowSums(count.table) == 0
sprintf("%s percent",round(sum(sel) * 100/ nrow(count.table),digits=1))
## [1] "25.7 percent"
sprintf("of %s genes are not expressed",nrow(count.table))
## [1] "of 70736 genes are not expressed"

Display the per-gene mean expression; i.e.Â the mean raw count of every gene across samples is calculated and displayed on a log10 scale

plot(density(log10(rowMeans(count.table))),col=pal[1],
     main="mean raw counts distribution",
     xlab="mean raw counts (log10)")

The same is done for the individual samples colored by sample type

pal=brewer.pal(8,"Dark2")
plot.multidensity(log10(count.table),col=sample(pal,length(res),TRUE),
                  legend.x="topright",legend.cex=0.5,
                  main="sample raw counts distribution",
                  xlab="per gene raw counts (log10)")

For visualization, the data is submitted to a variance stabilization transformation using DESeq2. The dispersion is estimated independently of the sample type.

conditions <- colnames(count.table)
dds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(
  countData = count.table,
  colData = data.frame(condition=conditions,
                       date=samples$Date,
                       tissue=samples$Tissue),
  design = ~ condition)

2.1 VST blind = TRUE

colData(dds)$condition <- factor(colData(dds)$condition,
                                 levels=unique(conditions))
vsd <- varianceStabilizingTransformation(dds, blind=TRUE)
vst <- assay(vsd)
vst <- vst - min(vst)

Visualize the corrected mean - sd relationship. It is not exactly linear, but we can still assume homoscedasticity for the purpose of QA.

meanSdPlot(vst)

2.1.1 PCA

Perform a Principal Component Analysis (PCA) of the data to do a quick quality assessment; i.e.Â replicate should cluster and the first dimensions should be explainable by biological means.

pc <- prcomp(t(vst))
percent <- round(summary(pc)$importance[2,]*100)

Plot the PCA 3 first dimensions

replicates <- factor(samples$Sampling)
colours <- ifelse(samples$Tissue=="Phloem",
                  cols[1],cols[2])

scatterplot3d(pc$x[,1],
              pc$x[,2],
              pc$x[,3],
              xlab=paste("Comp. 1 (",percent[1],"%)",sep=""),
              ylab=paste("Comp. 2 (",percent[2],"%)",sep=""),
              zlab=paste("Comp. 3 (",percent[3],"%)",sep=""),
              color=colours,
              pch=LETTERS[replicates])

2.2 VST blind = FALSE

We now redo the vst in a model aware fashion. The model is based on the previous knowledge as can be observed above that tissue and date are essential factors (20% and 45% (PC1 and PC3 cumulated), respectively)

design(dds) <- ~tissue + date
vsd <- varianceStabilizingTransformation(dds, blind=FALSE)
bst <- assay(vsd)
bst <- bst - min(bst)

The plot shows an almost ideal mean-sd relationship, the data looks almost perfectly homoscedastic.

meanSdPlot(bst)

2.2.1 PCA

The PCA looks very similar to the âblindâ one, but the first 3D explains 6% more of the overall variability!

pc <- prcomp(t(bst))
percent <- round(summary(pc)$importance[2,]*100)
scatterplot3d(pc$x[,1],
              pc$x[,2],
              pc$x[,3],
              xlab=paste("Comp. 1 (",percent[1],"%)",sep=""),
              ylab=paste("Comp. 2 (",percent[2],"%)",sep=""),
              zlab=paste("Comp. 3 (",percent[3],"%)",sep=""),
              color=colours,
              pch=LETTERS[replicates])

par(mar=mar)

2.3 Comparison

2.3.1 Basic

The matrices distribution show differences

plot.multidensity(list(blind=vst,controlled=bst),
                  xlab="~log2 (vst)",main="VST data comparison")

stopifnot(identical(dimnames(bst),dimnames(vst)))

Which appear to be frequent and highly variable

plot(density(vst - bst))

In a consistent manner

plot(density(rowMeans(vst - bst)))

plot(density(rowMedians(vst - bst)))

Affecting almost half of the genes

sum(rowMedians(vst - bst) != 0)
## [1] 36793

2.3.2 Heatmap

Looking at the 1000 most affected genes

sel <- order(rowMedians(vst - bst),decreasing=TRUE)[1:1000]

VST aware

heatmap.2(bst[sel,],labRow = NA,trace = "none",cexCol = 0.6 )

VST blind

heatmap.2(vst[sel,],labRow = NA,trace = "none",cexCol = 0.6 )

Aware with some extra info; the sampling times across the season (x axis labels) and the tissues (color code at the top, green == Phloem)

heatmap.2(bst[sel,],labRow = NA,trace = "none",cexCol = 0.6, scale="row",
          labCol=replicates,ColSideColors=colours)

Save the object for further assessment

save(dds,vst,bst,file="analysis/vst_blind-and-aware_results.rda")
